	  <title>The Norm Operation: Exercises</title>
	  <quiz>
		    <question>
			      <para>
            <para.body>Answer the following questions:</para.body>
         </para>
		    </question>
		    <part>
			      <question>
				        <para>
               <para.body>What is the norm of a vector?</para.body>
            </para>
			      </question>
			      <choice>
				        <answer>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Same as the distance between two points</para.body>
               </para>
				        </answer>
				        <info>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Not quite! While the formula for the distance between two points and the formula with which we compute the norm of a vector appear to be the same, the concepts of ‘distance between two points’ and ‘vector’ are very distinct. So the norm of a vector is not the same as the distance between two points.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </info>
			      </choice>
			      <choice>
				        <answer>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Same as the length of an arrow</para.body>
               </para>
				        </answer>
				        <info>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Almost right! - You need to specify which arrow you are taking the length of!</para.body>
               </para>
				        </info>
			      </choice>
			      <choice>
				        <answer>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>The norm of a vector <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math> is the length of any arrow representing <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </answer>
				        <info>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Correct!</para.body>
               </para>
				        </info>
			      </choice>
		    </part>
		    <part>
			      <question>
				        <para>
               <para.body>The norm of a vector is ... – What kind of information is required to complete this sentence?</para.body>
            </para>
			      </question>
			      <choice>
				        <answer>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>A point in 3-dimensional space</para.body>
               </para>
				        </answer>
				        <info>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Sorry, no!</para.body>
               </para>
				        </info>
			      </choice>
			      <choice>
				        <answer>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Some number</para.body>
               </para>
				        </answer>
				        <info>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Correct!</para.body>
               </para>
				        </info>
			      </choice>
			      <choice>
				        <answer>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Some number which is greater than or equal to <math>
                        <latex>0</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </answer>
				        <info>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Correct! – Notice that, while the previous answer was correct as well, it was less accurate than the answer given here.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </info>
			      </choice>
		    </part>
		    <part>
			      <question>
				        <para>
               <para.body>What is a unit vector?</para.body>
            </para>
			      </question>
			      <choice>
				        <answer>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Any vector in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[1]</latex>
                     </math>
					             </para.body>
               </para>
				        </answer>
				        <info>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>If this is what you think, please review the definition of a ‘unit vector’</para.body>
               </para>
				        </info>
			      </choice>
			      <choice>
				        <answer>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>A vector pointing in the direction of the first coordinate axis.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </answer>
				        <info>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Not necessarily! - The truth is: there are exactly two unit vectors which point in the direction of the first coordinate axis. – Which?</para.body>
               </para>
				        </info>
			      </choice>
			      <choice>
				        <answer>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>A unit vector is a vector of length <math>
                        <latex>1</latex>
                     </math>
					             </para.body>
               </para>
				        </answer>
				        <info>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Correct!</para.body>
               </para>
				        </info>
			      </choice>
		    </part>
		    <part>
			      <question>
				        <para>
               <para.body>How many unit vectors are there which are parallel to the third coordinate vector in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math>?</para.body>
            </para>
			      </question>
			      <choice>
				        <answer>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>One unit vector, namely <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{u} = (0,0,1) = \Vect{e}_3</latex>
                     </math>
					             </para.body>
               </para>
				        </answer>
				        <info>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>The vector <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{u}</latex>
                     </math> is a unit vector which is indeed parallel to the third coordinate axis. However, it is not the only unit vector.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </info>
			      </choice>
			      <choice>
				        <answer>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>There are infinitely many such unit vectors.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </answer>
				        <info>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Sorry, no! – Let's think this through carefully now: The third coordinate axis in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math> is a line. Now how many vectors of length <math>
                        <latex>1</latex>
                     </math> are there which are parallel to a given line?</para.body>
               </para>
				        </info>
			      </choice>
			      <choice>
				        <answer>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>There are two such unit vectors, namely <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{e}_3 = (0,0,1)</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>-\Vect{e}_3 = (0,0,-1)</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </answer>
			      </choice>
		    </part>
	  </quiz>
	
	
	
	
	
	  <exercise>
